"script": "If you're swimming in the ocean and suddenly realize you're being pulled away from the shore, You are likely caught in a rip current. Your first instinct will be to swim as hard as you can straight back toward the beach, But you must fight that urge. A rip current is a narrow, powerful stream of water that can drag even Olympic swimmers out to sea. Instead, you need to swim parallel to the shore. Rip currents are usually only a few dozen feet wide. Once you escape its pull, you can safely swim back to the beach.",
